{
  "Idea": "This research introduces a novel paradigm for emotion detection in text: modeling the Emotional Translation Gap through longitudinal, interactive annotation cycles between writers and readers. Rather than treating emotion labels as static ground truth derived from isolated annotations, this project conceptualizes emotional understanding as a dynamic, bidirectional process shaped by feedback and revision. We design a controlled human annotation study in which writers compose emotionally charged messages (e.g., apologies, confessions, requests) and self-report intended emotions using a nuanced taxonomy (e.g., Plutchik’s wheel + context-specific blends). These texts are then annotated by multiple readers who report perceived emotions and provide brief interpretive feedback (e.g., 'I read this as sarcastic'). Crucially, writers receive anonymized summaries of reader perceptions and are invited to revise their texts to better align with their intended emotional tone. This cycle repeats up to three times, generating traceable emotion trajectories for both expression and perception. The resulting dataset captures not only initial mismatches but also how linguistic choices evolve to bridge the gap—such as increased specificity, use of emoticons, or emotional intensifiers. We develop a new neural architecture, TrajectoEmoNet, a dual-path transformer with recurrent memory blocks that model temporal shifts in both writer strategy and reader interpretation. One path encodes textual revisions and predicts evolving expression intent; the other integrates reader subjectivity embeddings (demographics, empathy, mood) and predicts shifting perception distributions across rounds. A key innovation is the Emotion Alignment Loss, which jointly optimizes for accuracy in predicting both current state and future shift direction. We further introduce a Span-Level Discordance Analyzer—a module inspired by SpanEmo—that identifies specific tokens or spans most responsible for persistent misinterpretations, enabling explainable interventions. This framework enables AI systems to proactively detect high-risk emotional ambiguity and suggest revisions to improve cross-subjective clarity. Applications include emotionally intelligent writing assistants, bias-aware content moderation, and adaptive dialogue systems in therapy bots. All data, code, and models will be released publicly, including detailed logs of interaction dynamics and alignment metrics.",
